82      A HUFFING COURTIER.
pays himsself again in Inssolence over thosse, that
are below him; and with a generous Scorn
desspises those, that can neither do him good,
nor hurt.  He adores thoss, that may do him
good, though he knows they never will; and
desspisses thosse, that would not hurt him, if
they could.  The Court is his Church, and he
believes as that believes, and cries up and down
every Thing, as he finds it pass there.  It is a
great Comfort to him to think, that ssome who
do not know him may perhaps take him for a
Lord; and while that Thought lassts he looks
bigger than ussual, and forgets his Acquain-
tance ; and that's the Reasson why he will ssome-
times know you, and ssometimes not.  Nothing
but want of Money or Credit puts him in
mind that he is mortal ; but then he trussts
Providence that ssomebody will trusst him; and
in Expectation of that hopes for a better Life,
and that his Debts will never risse up in Judg-
ment against him.  To get in debt is to labour
in is Vocation; but to pay is to forfeit his
Protection; for what's the worth to one that
owes Nothing? His Employment being only to
wear his Cloaths, the whole Account of his
Life and Acttions is recorded in Shopkeepers
Books, that are his faithful Hisstoriographers to  
